JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 1445
EP  - 1455
VL  - 48
IS  - 4
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1993.tb04761.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT Most current empirical work finds no evidence that money shocks lower interest rates. We show that these nonresults are mainly due to a failure to model the conditional heteroskedasticity of interest rates. Autoregressive conditional heteroskedasticity (ARCH) models find a significant liquidity effect where ordinary least squares (OLS) models do not. The existence of a liquidity effect is found using different models and sample periods when ARCH models are used in estimation, but never when OLS is employed.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Irrelevance of Margin: Evidence from the Crash of '87
AU  - SEGUIN, PAUL J.
AU  - JARRELL, GREGG A.
Y1  - 1993/09/01
PY  - 1993
DA  - 1993/09/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1993.tb04762.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 1457
EP  - 1473
VL  - 48
IS  - 4
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1993.tb04762.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT Following the crash of 1987, one contentious regulatory issue has been whether margin activity exacerbated the decline in equity values. We contrast the crash behavior of NASDAQ securities eligible for margin trading with the behavior of ineligible ones. Consistent with the hypothesis that margin-eligible securities were more frequently subjected to margin calls and forced sales, we find that abnormal volumes were uniformly larger for eligible securities. However, there is no evidence that this activity provoked additional price depreciation. Margin-eligible securities actually fell by one percent less than the ineligible securities over the period.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Crowding Out and the Informativeness of Security Prices
AU  - PAUL, JONATHAN M.
Y1  - 1993/09/01
PY  - 1993
DA  - 1993/09/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1993.tb04763.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 1475
EP  - 1496
VL  - 48
IS  - 4
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1993.tb04763.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT Individual investors trade less agressively on any particular piece of information as more investors observe it. The trades of the new investors observing a piece of information ?crowd out? some of the trades of the old investors who observe that same piece of information. This paper shows that when traders are risk averse, these crowding out effects lead the proportions of traders who choose to observe one signal versus another to differ from the proportions that maximize the informativeness of prices.
ER  - 

